le(true)\\n    val extractor: Object = constructor.newInstance(Type.of[LowPriority.type])\\n    val unapply: java.lang.reflect.Method = extractorClass.getDeclaredMethod(\\n      \\\"unapply\\\",\\n      classOf[Expr[?]],\\n      classOf[Quotes]\\n    )\\n    unapply.setAccessible(true)\\n    val extracted: Option[ValueOf[LowPriority.type]] = unapply\\n      .invoke(extractor, valueOfExpr, quotes)\\n      .asInstanceOf[Option[ValueOf[LowPriority.type]]]\\n\\n    if (extracted.exists(_.value == LowPriority)) {\\n      Expr(true)\\n    } else {\\n      report.errorAndAbort(\\\"ValueEnumMacros did not extract the singleton module\\\")\\n    }\\n  }\\n}\\n\", \"newText\": \"}\\n\"}]}\n3661:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Exploring Scala 3 ASTs**\\n\\nI'm pondering whether New(TypeTree.of[ValueOf]) might represent something that's already been applied. I need to dive deeper into Scala 3's Abstract Syntax Trees (AST) specifically for `new ValueOf[T](LowPriority)`. It crosses my mind that while I could instrument this for testing, I can't really run tests on it right now. Instead of relying on a runtime compilation macro for finding values, perhaps I could use the existing ValueOfFromExprProbe, tweaking it to create Ident using quotes more accurately.\\n\\n**Considering code organization**\\n\\nI need to think about cleaning up some code. Perhaps I could remove unused imports like Type Expr Quotes if there's no probe. Also, I wonder if I should remove the main build if it’s not necessary. It looks like src/main needs to exist, but keeping it is essential. If there’s no main in Scala, I know the priority should be on the main. I also need to ensure Yretain-trees compiles both main and runtime.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_05c8c20709c6133c0169fb990788e881979acd4fc2862dcd28\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp-5kerCViJBg7ATxk